summary: I tried to hide my true feelings, but whatever, there is the ongoing second season of Killing Eve, and I am on a spree. The most...
body:
I tried to hide my true feelings, but whatever, there is the ongoing second season of Killing Eve, and I am on a spree. The most important thing that this series made me realize is how low are the standards for straight onscreen romance. The situation in Killing Eve is by no means the one I would root for, and yet, it pulls it off with the insane chemistry between the actresses and in the script itself, in all the imagery and symbolism that surrounds them. And here we have a billion of sloppy straight stories where, to add to all toxicity, the actors barely try to hide their indifference to each other, and the scripts probably have the line “They are of opposite sex, therefore they are in love” somewhere, and the straights™ praise each of them as the Love Story for the Ages. Like, it’s just sloppy.

Also, what’s Hugo’s area of expertise besides being posh and white? He seems useless.

summary: There’s quite a bit of Sandra content on twitter and tumblr (currently there’s an interview with her in Ottawa).  I think it...
question: There’s quite a bit of Sandra content on twitter and tumblr (currently there’s an interview with her in Ottawa).  I think it gets buried in the rest of the fandom though :/
answer:
yeah, it definitely gets buried. i always love the insightful things she has to say about eve. she really digs deep into her characters. 

i mean, it makes sense. jodie is around the age of the majority of people in our fandom. she posts more often. makes her life more public. it makes sense that her content would rise to the top. she’s more relatable. 

it’s also that sandra’s performance as eve was pretty subtle in the first season. it is very Obvious that jodie is an amazing actress from season 1. eve’s arc was WAY more lowkey. this season, she’s really popping off. eve is going fucking insane, and, damn, is sandra sinking her TEETH into it.
